"How many loaves do you have?" asked Jesus. "Seven," they answered, "and a few small fish."
Jesus said to the crowds, "Sit down on the ground."
He took the seven loaves and the fish and gave thanks. Then he broke them and gave them to the disciples, and the disciples gave them to the people.
They all ate and were satisfied. Afterwards, the disciples picked up seven baskets of the leftover fragments.
The number of men who ate was 4000. Women and children also ate.
After Jesus had dismissed the crowd, he got into the boat and went to the region of Magadan.
Jesus is asked for a sign of a miracle.
The Pharisees and Sadducees came to test Jesus. They asked him to show them a miraculous sign from heaven.
He replied: "In the evening you look at the sky. You say: The weather will be good. The sky is red."
In the morning you say, "It will rain today. The sky is red and cloudy." You know the meaning of what you see in the sky. But you don't understand the signs of what's happening now.
The unbelieving people sought a miraculous sign, but they will receive only the sign of Jonah. Then Jesus left them and went away. The Pharisees and Sadducees gathered together.
The pupils crossed to the other side of the lake. They forgot to bring the bread.
"Beware," Jesus said to them, "Beware of the leaven of the Pharisees and Sadducees."
The pupils spoke among themselves about this. They said, "He must be saying this because we didn't bring any bread."
Jesus knew what they were saying. He said to them, "You of little faith! Why do you discuss among yourselves that you have no bread?"
Don't you understand yet? Don't you remember the five loaves for 5000? Don't you remember how many baskets full of pieces you gathered?
Do you not remember the five loaves of the five thousand, and how many baskets full of fragments you gathered?
How can you not understand? I was not talking to you about bread. But beware of the leaven of the Pharisees and Sadducees.
Then the disciples understood that Jesus did not tell them to beware of the leaven of bread, but he warned them of the teaching of the Pharisees and Sadducees, in the way of Peter that Jesus is the Christ.
Jesus went to the region of Caesarea Philippi. There he asked his disciples, "Who do people say the Son of Man is?"
They replied, "Some say it is John the Baptist; others say Elijah; still others, Jeremiah or one of the prophets."
"But what about you?" he asked. "Who do you say that I am?"
Simon Peter answered, "You are the Christ, the Son of the living God."
Jesus answered, "Blessed are you, Simon son of Jonah! For flesh and blood has not revealed this to you, but my Father who is in heaven."
This is what I tell you. You are Peter. On this rock I will build my church. The gates of hell will not be strong enough to destroy it.
I will give you the keys of the kingdom of heaven. Whatever you bind on earth will be bound in heaven, and whatever you loose on earth will be loosed in heaven.
Then Jesus charged his disciples that they should tell no man that he was the Christ. Jesus speaks of his coming death.
From that time on Jesus began to explain to his disciples that he must go to Jerusalem and suffer many things at the hands of the elders, chief priests and teachers of the law. He must be killed and on the third day be raised to life.
Peter took Jesus aside and began to rebuke him. "Never, Lord!" he said. "This must never happen to you!"
Jesus turned and said to Peter, "Get behind me, Satan! You are a stumbling block to me; for you are not setting your mind on the things of God, but on the things of man."
Then Jesus said to his disciples, "If anyone would come after me, let him deny himself and take up his cross and follow me."
If he wants to save his life, he will lose it. But if he loses his life for my sake, he will find it.
"What good is it for someone to gain the whole world and yet lose their soul? Or what can anyone give in exchange for their soul?"
The Son of Man will come in the glory of his Father, with his angels, and then he will reward each one according to his works.
"Truly I tell you, I will not drink again from the fruit of the vine until that day when I drink it new in the kingdom of God." "Some who are standing here will not taste death until they see the Son of Man coming in his kingdom."
The appearance of Jesus changes his form.
After six days Jesus took Peter, James, and John, his brother, and led them up to a high mountain by themselves.
There before them, his appearance changed. His face shone like the sun. His clothes became white as light.
At that moment, Moses and Elijah appeared before them. Moses and Elijah were speaking with Jesus.
Peter said to Jesus, "Lord, it is good that we are here. If you wish, let us make three tents: one for you, one for Moses, and one for Elijah."
While Peter was still speaking, a bright cloud enveloped them. And a voice from the cloud said, "This is my beloved Son, with whom I am well pleased. Listen to him!"
When the disciples heard this, they were troubled. They came to him and bowed down to the ground.
But Jesus came and touched them. He said to them, "Arise. Do not be afraid."
So when they raised their eyes toward the sky, they saw nothing but Jesus.
They came down from the mountain. On the way, Jesus told them what to do. "Don't tell anyone what you saw," he said. "Wait until the Son of Man has risen from the dead."
The disciples asked him, "Why then do the scribes say that Elijah must come first?"
Jesus replied, "So it is written." Elijah is to come first and restore all things.
But I say to you, Elijah has come, and they did not recognize him, but did to him whatever they pleased. So also will the Son of Man suffer at their hands.
Then the disciples understood that Jesus was speaking to them about John the Baptist. Jesus fed a boy from whom a demon had been cast out.
As they approached the crowd, a man came up to Jesus. He knelt down before him.
"My lord," he said, "have mercy on my son. He is trembling severely and suffering greatly. He often falls into the fire or into the water."
I brought him to your disciples, but they could not heal him.
"You faithless and evil people!" Jesus answered. "How long must I stay with you? How long must I put up with you?"
Jesus commanded the demon to come out of the boy, and it did. He was healed instantly.
Then the disciples came to Jesus in private and asked, "Why couldn't we cast it out?"
He replied, "Because your faith is so small. What I am about to tell you is true. If you have faith as small as a mustard seed, you can say to this mountain, 'Move from here to there,' and it will move. Nothing will be impossible for you."
